        <a class="anchor" id="robustness-analysis"></a>
        <h2 class="title is-3">Robustness Analysis</h2>

        <a class="anchor" id="length-robustness"></a>
        <h3 class="title is-4">Robusetness to Unseen Test-Time Lengths</h3>
        <div class="content has-text-justified">
          <p>
            We evaluate <span class="dmethod">PERK</span>&apos;s robustness to inputs of different lengths than those seen in training.
            We test for both <em>shorter</em> and <em>longer</em> test-time lengths than the training length.
            We evaluate using the BabiLong tasks and train a Qwen-2.5-0.5B model using <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> on fixed-length contexts ranging from 1K to 8K tokens.
            We evaluate each model on contexts ranging from 1K to 32K tokens, measuring each approach's ability to generalize to unseen lengths.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="figure-container" style="width: 60%; margin: 0 auto;">
          <figure class="image mod-figure">
            <img src="/static/images/length-generalization_updated.png" alt="test-time length extrapolation">
          </figure>
          <div class="table-caption">
            <strong>Robusetness to unseen test-time lengths</strong> on BabiLong <strong>QA1 (a)</strong> and <strong>QA2 (b)</strong>
            comparison between <span class="highlight-text">PERK (Ours)</span> and FT-ICR on the Qwen-2.5-0.5B model.
            The y-axis represents the training context lengths, while the x-axis indicates various test-time context lengths.
            Bordered cells denote the boundary: evaluation on context lengths equal to those in training.
            <strong><span class="highlight-text">PERK (Ours)</span> shows stronger robustness to unseen test-time lengths.</strong>
          </div>
        </div>
        <br/>

        <strong>On longer test-time lengths:</strong> FT-ICR's performance drops drastically as the inference context length exceeds the training context length,
        especially for models trained on shorter contexts.
        While <span class="dmethod">PERK</span>&apos;s accuracy also decreases (from a higher starting point), the degradation is dampened at longer test lengths.

        <br/><br/>

        <strong>On shorter test-time lengths:</strong> FT-ICR continues to lose performance on shorter contexts when finetuned on longer ones,
        matching observations from <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.02660" target="_blank">Gao et al. (2025)</a>.
        In contrast, <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> maintains its performance and even increases performance for QA2.

        <br/><br/>

        <h4 class="title is-5">PERK generalizes to long context lengths beyond the context window.</h4>

